marily driven by the company\'s strategy to rapidly scale compute infrastructure. Major cost factors include:\n*   Depreciation of GPU hardware.\n*   Higher cloud computing and data center infrastructure expenses (facilities-related costs).\n*   Increased employee compensation expenses.\n*   **Future Outlook:** The company expects a **"multi-year investment horizon"** before terrestrial and orbital data center deployments translate into sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA. Capital expenditures will scale as quickly as power and compute can be deployed to capture a $26.5 trillion potential market opportunity.\n\n---\n\n### 2. X Platform Advertising Revenue Trends\nWhile the AI segment is pivoting heavily toward AI solutions, infrastructure, and subscriptions, advertising on the X platform remains a core component of its revenue mix. The advertising revenue has experienced notable volatility over the past few years:\n\n*   **Q1 2026 (Temporary Dip):** Advertising revenue **decreased by $100 million** year-over-year. This decline was a temporary anomaly caused by an "overhaul of the Company’s advertising platform," which impacted ad sales during the rebuild period. (Overall AI revenue still grew by $91 million due to a $191 million surge in AI solutions, Grok, and X subscriptions).\n*   **Full Year 2025 (Recovery):** Advertising revenue **increased by $116 million** (22.2% overall segment revenue growth). This recovery was driven by increased advertising spend from partners on the X platform.\n*   **Full Year 2024 (Significant Contraction):** Advertising revenue **decreased by $595 million**. This sharp drop was attributed to the "loss of advertising partners for X," which caused total AI segment revenue to decline by $341 million overall, despite growth in subscriptions and data licensing.\n\n**Seasonality and Recognition Policies:**\n*   **Seasonality:** Advertising revenues experience distinct seasonality. Spend is typically **highest in the fourth quarter** 